180. Drug Alcohol Depend. 1984 Mar;13(2):107-16. doi:
10.1016/0376-8716(84)90050-4.

International drug treaties: the connexion between ratification and social and 
economic conditions.

Smart RG, Murray GF.

This study examines social and economic conditions in 152 countries and relates 
them to ratification of the two major international drug control treaties , the 
Single Convention on Narcotic Drugs and the Convention on Psychotropic 
Substances. The findings show that: (i) countries which ratified only the Single 
Convention had the greatest drug problems; (ii) ratifications were more common 
among developed countries than developing ones; (iii) ratifications were not 
more common among larger countries or those having higher expenditures on health 
and education, but they were more common among older U.N. member countries and 
those having ratified more non-drug treaties ; (iv) the best predictors of 
ratifications were a high level of life expectancy, a high degree of economic 
development and a substantial drug problem. The trend has been for more 
countries to ratify these treaties over time. However, a shorter-term solution 
would involve international support for those poorer countries which have not 
yet ratified them. Technical advice in the form of legal experts and translators 
is one example of such support.

DOI: 10.1016/0376-8716(84)90050-4
